The line of the exception is in this method:

  public String getString(String key)
  {
    return Platform.getResourceBundle(plugin.getBundle()).getString(key);
  }

so the only way that this could have a null pointer exception is if the resource
bundle is missing, which I've seen only in cases where the installation is
corrupted.

I think you should try installing a fresh image.  (Or try removing the
eclipse/configuration directory or running with the -clean option.)
